JSON – Java script Object Notation (Data Format)
It is a lightweight, text-based, language-independent data interchange format used to store and transport data, often between servers and web applications.

What is JSON?
•	JSON – Java Script Object Notation
•	JSON is a syntax for storing and exchanging data.
•	It was designed for human-readable data interchange.
•	JASON is text, written with Java Script Object Notation
•	It has been extended from the JavaScript scripting language
•	The filename extension is .json
•	JSON internet Media type is application/json

JSON Data Types
•	Number Not required Quotations
•	String  Required Quotations “ “
•	Boolean (Ture/False)  it is not required Quotations
•	Null (Unknown value)Value in json can be null  not required Quotations
•	Object (Contains the multiple records)
•	Array  whenever your using double value use [ 1234, 4567 ] square brackets

Enter JSON will be presented in the Key: Value pair

Data Types with examples

1>String – String in JSON must be written in double quotes.
Example:
	{ “name” :  “Rohit” }

2>Number – Number in JSON must be an integer or a floating point.
Example:
	{  “Age” : 30 }

3>Object – Values in JSON can be objects.
Example:
	{
	“employee” : { “name” : “Rohit”, “age” : 35, “City” : “Belgaum”}
	}


Key is always included in the “” Quotations

{
“Name” : “Rohit”
“Middle name” : null
“Age” : 35
“Phone” : [ 12345, 56789]
“Status” : true
}
Name and Age are here Keys
Rohit and 35 are the values.
If the string is there you need to add “” Quotations.
If the value is number, no need of “” Quotations.


